[[Air Chief Marshal]] '''Sir Ronald Andrew Fellowes Wilson''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KCB|AFC|FRAeS}} (born 27 February 1941), often known as '''Sir Andrew Wilson''' and sometimes known informally as '''Sir Sandy Wilson''', is a retired senior [[Royal Air Force]] officer.

==RAF career==
Educated at [[Tonbridge School]], Wilson joined the Royal Air Force in 1962. From 1976 to 1978 Wilson served as the Commanding Officer of [[No. 2 Squadron RAF|No. II (AC) Squadron]].<ref>[http://www.twosqnassoc.co.uk/pages/bosses/bosses.htm The Commanding Officers of II(AC) Squadron]</ref>  During this time the Squadron took delivery of the [[SEPECAT Jaguar|Jaguar]] which Wilson oversaw, flying practice reconnaissance missions.<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1976/1976%20-%201076.html Defence] Flight International, 26 June 1976</ref> In 1980 Wilson was made Station Commander of [[RAF Lossiemouth]].<ref>[http://www.rafweb.org/Stations/Station%20OCs-Scot.htm Air of Authority – A History of RAF Organisation – RAF Station Commanders – Scotland, North-East England and Northern Ireland]</ref>

In 1990 Wilson was appointed the Commander British Forces Middle East, making him the in-theatre commander for [[Operation Granby]], the British contribution to the [[Gulf War]]. He was knighted in 1991<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=52563 |date=14 June 1991 |startpage=3 |supp=x |accessdate=12 October 2008}}</ref> and in 1993 he was appointed [[Air Member for Personnel]]<ref>[http://www.rafweb.org/AirMin2.htm Air of Authority – A History of RAF Organisation – Air Council Appointments 1]</ref> and the following year, on 1 April 1994, Wilson became the first Air Officer Commander-in-Chief of [[RAF Personnel and Training Command|Personnel and Training Command]]. 

==Retirement==
He retired prematurely on 26 August 1995.<ref>{{LondonGazette |issue=54167 |date= 25 September 1995 |startpage=12997 |supp=x |accessdate=23 November 2008}}</ref>  He was accused of using government funds to refurbish Haymes Garth, the official residence for the Air Member for Personnel based at RAF Innsworth.<ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/ousting-of-raf-chief-was-fair-say-officers-1572458.html</ref>  He argued that he used funds budgeted for this purpose, but was not supported by the then Defence Minister, Sir [[Malcolm Rifkind]].

